 `res.locals` does not persist to the next route.  The `res` object applies ONLY to this particular request.  Only `req.session` will be preserved for future routes for that user.  You will have to re-assign `res.locals` in the next route before you call `res.render()` in that next route.  

So, when you do this:

                req.session.isLoggedIn = true;
                res.locals.isLoggedIn = true;
                res.redirect(&#39;/&#39;);

`res.redirect(&#39;/&#39;)` sends a response to the browser.  That request is now done. 
 Then the browser processes the redirect and makes a NEW request to the server for the `/` route.  The value of `res.locals` you just set will be gone when the new `/` route gets hit after the redirect is processed by the browser.

So, in all routes where you want to use the session data in the rendered template, read data from `req.session` and set `res.locals` appropriately for the template you&#39;re about to render.

